@ThinkingandTinkering that is why I used them and the best place I found them at was in inline skates at the thrift stores (a buck or two during the winter when no one will want them as they are warm weather sport items,) and there are 8 of them in each side, so you get 16 bearings like you used for a buck or two, then I would run WD 40 through them while spinning them to make it drain and wash through them to clean them out. following it up with an oil (3-in-one is my choice) then I got so many to clean I designed a small PVC pipe fitting system that I could then clamp a piece of allthread through it and into a drill chuck 

the PVC fittings I had some room left at the top so I could fill the area with the cleaner and it stays quite a long time with no changes but once I start spinning the rod inside it, and the bearings thus internal race, the oil drains through and flushes out all the gunk and grit leaving them smooth and free rolling like new (as long as they did not get ground up with something inside) I still have the PVC fitting system and may one day use them again though you can find a ton of bearings too in things like old hard drives and the like, 

whole point too to the system was I was able to flip the bearing system around where the shafts were outside a core shaft so a larger item can be supported and freed up for rotation on them with out going "around" them from the central hole in them :) and the grub screw system if you use a couple extra you can then use to adjust things to tighten them up if it requires some super tight and aligned movement or something to get that say super tight clearance to maximize their reactions like magnets and coils all without breaking the bank, just toss a little extra elbow grease and get it done. :) (my mill was made mostly of MDF and found metal bits, and could literally mill 4 different layers deep into a single sheet of paper, so anything is possible if someone just puts it in their mind. and then keeps at trying those different things till they get what they want. :)
